namespace Pscf {
namespace Rp {

/*! 
\page rp_ShiftMove_page ShiftMove

The ShiftMove performs a Monte Carlo move that rigidly translates the
current fields by a random displacement. It is designed to be used 
to speed up sampling in Einstein crystal thermodynamic integration 
simulations under conditions in which the bias introduced by the
perturbation is almost turned off. 

\see Rp::ShiftMove (class API)

\section rp_ShiftMove_algorithm_sec Step Algorithm

The shift move translates the field by displacement that corresponds
to a shift by an integer number of grid points in each direction. 
The parameter maxShift is an integer that gives the maximum allowed 
displacement in each direction. Displacements are chosen uniformly
from the range between -maxShift and +maxShift.

\section rp_ShiftMove_parameter_sec Parameter File

An example of the associated parameter file block is shown below.
\code
  ShiftMove{
    probability   0.5
    maxShift         2
  }
\endcode
The format for this block is thus:
\code
  ShiftMove{
    probability  float (in range [0,1])
    maxShift      int 
  }
\endcode
The meanings of the two required parameter are summarized briefly below:
<table>
  <tr>
    <td> <b> Label </b>  </td>
    <td> <b> Description </b>  </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> probability </td>
    <td> probability of attempting a move of this type  </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> maxShift </td>
    <td> maximum absolute value of the shift in any direction. </td>
  </tr>
</table>

*/

}
}
